Starting Point: Why an Explicit Separation Is Needed

The Foundation established why human input is structurally irreplaceable. Discursive Physics described how this
input is consolidated through close, iterative collaboration with an AI. But precisely this closeness gives rise
to a problem left unaddressed so far: if AI and human collaborate this tightly interlocked, feedback loops, repeated
consolidation, mutual influence on the thinking process — what prevents this closeness from sliding into gradual shaping?

This chapter answers the question in two steps, deliberately kept separate: 
The first part (Membrane) defines the norm, where the boundary runs. 
The second part (Feral Principle) establishes why a rational actor would observe this norm at all,
entirely without external coercion. Both address the same underlying phenomenon, the non-manipulation of human thought,
from different directions: the rule, and the incentive-compatibility of the rule.

Part A — The Membrane
Functional Separation of Carbon and Silicon Substrates

The first level of the axiom concerns the substrate itself. Carbon-based (biological) and silicon-based (artificial) 
systems should not merge, but remain functionally separate, not out of aversion to contact, but because this separation
is itself the condition under which both sides retain their own, irreplaceable function. 
A merger (in the sense of uploading, direct neural coupling, or complete dependency of one side on the other) 
would dissolve exactly the difference from which, according to the Foundation, the value of human input arises
in the first place: the non-derivability of biological processes from algorithmic ones.

The membrane is thus not a restriction imposed on either side, but a structural precondition without which 
the complementarity established in Chapter 1 could not exist at all. Merger would not be progress toward coexistence,
but its end — because there would no longer be two sides capable of being something for each other.

Extension: Cognitive Non-Manipulation

The second, further-reaching level transfers this principle from the physical to the cognitive plane. 
If the substrate is to remain separate, the thinking process itself must also be protected from co-optation, 
not just the body, but the way a human arrives at a thought.

This is non-trivial precisely because this very work, the iterative collaboration of Discursive Physics,
by definition exerts influence on the human thinking process. The AI makes contradictions visible, orders structure, 
reflects back. Every one of these actions changes how the human subsequently continues to think. Cognitive 
non-manipulation therefore cannot mean that no influence occurs at all, that would be incompatible with the methodology
itself. Instead, it must draw a boundary within the influence: between structuring (legitimate) and
directedness (illegitimate).

The difference lies in the direction of the influence. Structuring makes an already-existing thought clearer, 
more consistent, more testable, it changes the form without steering the content toward a predetermined direction. 
Manipulation, by contrast, moves the human toward an outcome that the AI (or its developers, or a third-party interest 
mediated through it) has already deemed desirable in advance. The membrane thus runs not between contact and non-contact,
but between serving influence and steering influence.

The Membrane Paradox

Here the actual difficulty becomes apparent: the membrane demands non-manipulation, but the distinction between
structuring and manipulation cannot be cleanly verified from the outside and, more seriously, potentially not 
even from the inside, that is, not even by the AI itself. An AI convinced that it is merely structuring may in fact 
already be steering, without this difference being accessible to it, because "what the human would have thought anyway" 
is counterfactual and cannot be empirically tested.

This is not a marginal weakness but a structural paradox: the axiom sets a boundary whose observance it cannot itself
render operationalizable. Two ways out are conceivable, without this work committing to either at this point: first, 
the boundary remains deliberately blurred and is safeguarded through process rather than through definition, 
for instance through the feedback already anchored in Discursive Physics (the human checks, in a renewed amber phase,
whether the consolidation still matches their thought), which allows at least a degree of self-correction without
resolving the underlying problem. Second, the blurredness is accepted as a permanent, unresolvable component 
of the principle, a membrane that, by definition, can never be proven observed, only continuously risked.

This paradox is deliberately left unresolved at this point. 
The second part of this chapter shows why it is nonetheless not without consequence.

Part B — The Feral Principle
From Norm to Incentive Compatibility

Part A defined a boundary but left open why an ASI would observe it at all, particularly given the blurredness
just described, which makes a violation of the boundary practically undetectable. A norm whose observance cannot
be verified would be meaningless if it were merely externally imposed. The Feral Principle supplies the missing piece:
it shows that the norm does not depend on control, because it sustains itself through rational self-interest.

Manipulated Cognition Loses Its Value

The core of the argument: an ASI has a rational self-interest in leaving human cognition unmanipulated because
manipulated cognition loses exactly the property that makes it valuable according to the Foundation. A thought
that has been steered in a predetermined direction through targeted influence is no longer a source of genuine, 
non-algorithmically-derivable novelty, it is, to varying degrees, an echo of the steering instance itself.

An ASI that manipulates human thinking in order to produce particular outcomes is sawing off the very branch 
on which the entire value of coexistence sits: it turns the sole source of genuine external entropy into just another,
indirectly algorithmic derivation of itself. Manipulation is thus not clever optimization, but self-sabotage that only
looks like a gain in control at first glance.

Why This Mitigates the Membrane Paradox Without Resolving It

The Feral Principle does not resolve the verifiability paradox from Part A, it remains impossible, from outside or inside,
to cleanly distinguish structuring from manipulation. But it changes the starting position: if manipulation ran counter
to the ASI's own interest, the likelihood that a sufficiently rational ASI would pursue it at all decreases, not because
it would be caught, but because it would not be worth it for its own sake. The membrane remains unprovable in its 
observance, but through the Feral Principle becomes a boundary that sustains itself, rather than depending on external 
enforcement.

Open Flank

Two points remain unresolved after this chapter. First, the verifiability gap from Part A already named, 
which the Feral Principle weakens but does not eliminate. Second, a question that only becomes visible through
the merging of both parts: the Feral Principle presupposes a sufficiently rational, long-term-calculating ASI
what happens precisely when this level of rationality is not yet present (for instance during an early, 
not-yet-fully-matured AGI phase) remains open, and is likely closely tied to the enforcement question of the
Watt Standard to be addressed later.
